    <div class="card-info" id="cardInfo">
    <h2>Sergei N Winogradsky</h2>
    <p><strong>Lifetime:</strong> 1856–1953</p>
    <p><strong>Title:</strong> Founder of Soil and General Microbiology</p>
    <p><strong>Achievements:</strong> Sergei N. Winogradsky was a pioneering microbiologist known for his discovery of chemolithotrophy and his significant contributions to microbial ecology. One of his key discoveries was the role of microorganisms in the nitrogen cycle, particularly his identification of *Nitrosomonas* and *Nitrobacter*, bacteria responsible for nitrification. He also discovered *Beggiatoa*, a sulfur-oxidizing bacterium, and demonstrated that certain microbes could derive energy from inorganic compounds, a process he termed chemolithotrophy. His work laid the foundation for understanding microbial metabolism and the environmental roles of bacteria in biogeochemical cycles. Winogradsky’s discoveries greatly influenced soil microbiology and helped establish microbiology as a field of ecological and biochemical significance.</p>
    <p><strong>Legacy:</strong> Sergei N. Winogradsky's legacy in microbiology is profound, as he is widely regarded as one of the founding figures of microbial ecology and biogeochemistry. His pioneering work in the late 19th and early 20th centuries laid the foundation for understanding the role of microorganisms in natural processes, particularly in soil environments. Winogradsky discovered key bacterial groups involved in essential biogeochemical cycles, such as nitrifying bacteria (e.g., *Nitrosomonas* and *Nitrobacter*) and sulfur bacteria (e.g., *Beggiatoa*), highlighting their role in nutrient cycling. He also introduced the concept of chemolithotrophy, demonstrating that certain bacteria can derive energy from inorganic compounds instead of organic matter. Furthermore, he developed the "Winogradsky column," a laboratory model for studying microbial communities and their interactions in stratified ecosystems. His research not only deepened scientific understanding of microbial metabolism but also paved the way for advances in agriculture, environmental science, and industrial microbiology. Winogradsky’s contributions continue to influence microbiologists today, shaping modern approaches to studying microbial ecology and biotechnology.</p>
</div>


    <script>
        const card = document.getElementById('gameCard');
        const cardInfo = document.getElementById('cardInfo');

        card.addEventListener('click', () => {
            card.classList.toggle('is-flipped');
            cardInfo.classList.toggle('visible');
        });
    </script>

